HEADWORD: Culverin
<hw>Cul"ver*in</hw> <pr>(k?l"v?r-?n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>coulevrine</ets>, prop. fem. of <ets>couleuvrin</ets> like a
serpent, fr. <ets>couleuvre</ets> adder, fr. L. <ets>coluber</ets>,
<ets>colubra</ets>.]</ety> <def>A long cannon of the 16th century,
usually an 18-pounder with serpent-shaped handles.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Trump, and drum, and roaring <qex>culverin</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Culverkey</ent>⟦br⟧
